text:
qanon fans are applying this same participatory behavior that we have celebrated in fiction fandom to real-world political drama. and why not? the boundaries between politics and entertainment have been collapsing for years. the entire trump presidency operates like reality tv, completely divorced from any real stakes or substance.

thatâ€™s what makes this all so terrifying. do these people really believe that tom hanks and hillary clinton are personally running a massive pedophilia ring? really??? but consider this: trump announced at a rally this week that the farmers being harmed by his stupid trade war had told him â€œwe can take it.â€ no actual farmers said that to him. we all know that. but itâ€™s a little thing, just part of the story we are all interacting with.

the pulsating heart of the qanon theory is not a lunatic fringe denying the real consequences of a failing presidency. the heart of it is a devoted fan base constructing elaborate theories to make the story more fun and engaging. and if you start from the premise that nothing government does matters, then itâ€™s easy to come along for the ride. thereâ€™s no real difference between hillary clinton and the smoke monster. theyâ€™re both just characters on the television.

thatâ€™s what alarms me most about the growth of qanon. itâ€™s not that these people are unhinged and possibly armed. itâ€™s that weâ€™ve lost the capacity to treat civics, governance, and public affairs as though they have actual stakes with actual consequences. the premise of the trump presidency is that nothing matters, so you should root for your side and heckle the opposing team. he encourages his supporters to treat democrats and journalists like a rival fan base.

david karpf

text:
the campaign â€” #letherspeak â€” aims to amend the laws so any survivor over the age of 18 can waive their right to anonymity if they so choose, without risking punishment to themselves or any media outlet which publishes their story with consent. 
in #tasmania and the #nt it is not legal for victims of sexual assault to ever share their story in the public sphere. effectively silencing their voices and ability to tell their stories and accounts. 
we are lobbying to change these laws. 
it would be great if #insta folks could sign the petition for change here: https://www.megaphone.org.au/petitions/let-her-speak?bucket=&source=twitter-share-button

text:
facebook showed me this post from a year ago. it's now been two years since life changed forever. i'm simultaneously more fearful and more hopeful than ever.
.
.
at precisely this time a year ago, one of the darkest periods of my life began. as it became clear our country, including some of my closest friends and family, had elected a morally-repugnant, highly unqualified and volatile man to the presidency, i fell into a hole so deep i thought i would never find my way out again. my heart felt broken. i cried for days, fearing for the dark times i knew laid ahead for so many groups of people.
.
.
i'm not a religious person, but the sunday after the election, i found myself at a church whose minister takes social justice to a level i'd never seen among christians. while he himself was still reeling from the election results, he told those gathered that day to not lose hope. he reminded us that history's greatest periods of progress followed, indeed were catalyzed by, the darkest of times.
.
.
dred scott was a few years before lincolnâ€™s election. .
.
the great depression preceded the new deal. .
.
progressive advances in the 60s and 70s came just after mccarthyism.
.
.
soon it became clear that, nightmarish and earth-shattering as this election & its aftermath have been, a sleeping giant was awakened on november 8, 2016. people have become more engaged in politics than i've ever seen in my lifetime, attending marches and rallies; donating money to organizations who would combat the fearful agenda put before us; finally, finally beginning to understand that we are not at the mercy of whoever is elected president. power doesn't just reside in the highest office in the land, but with us, the people. .
.
and here we are, one year later. still reeling, to be sure, but fighting like hell for what, i must periodically remind myself, the majority of our country knows to be right. and if the results of last night's elections tell us anything, with the election of people of color, women & lgbt politicians to positions previously only occupied by white men, it's that that sleeping giant isn't going to be lying down anytime soon.
.
.
#resist on, friends. happy anniversary.

text:
colabs conversations, hosted by the college of liberal arts & behavioral sciences and odei.

this is an important student forum, lead by a panel from the college, to discuss issues that affects students on campus. this particular conversation revolves around consent, accountability, and sexuality. this is in the wake of the #metoo and #timesup movements and the kavanuagh hearings...national issues and conversations that affect us right home!

wednesday, 11/14 at 11am-12pm and at 1pm-2pm in pab 114. (attend either session). snacks provided!

come join the conversation. your voice and experiences are important and need to be heard!
.
.
.

text:

.
each year the @willametteweek awards this special honor to young leaders working to make #portland a better place. no one is more deserving of this than christina.
.
for more than 8 years she has provided leadership in a variety of critical roles at @raphaelhousepdx. she now oversees our emergency shelter and housing programs, guiding a team of 21 advocates and ensuring that families we serve receive the best possible support.
.
a survivor herself, christina advocates tirelessly for all those in our programs, and her accolades are many. .
click the link in our bio to read more, and show your support for her and all our work at #raphaelhouse!

ğŸ˜… #savage #howitsdone #fucktrump â€” @snoopdogg has always been a character. we've loved him for years as he's turned into the uncle we all wish we had.
-
at times, he's funny. at others, he can spit some real talk. sometimes, he combines the two to send a message. tuesday's midterm elections were a major story in the united states with many artists urging their fans to get out and vote.
-
#donaldtrump has been critiqued heavily for his unconventional tactics as trump and snoop has been a major source of scrutiny. he decided to make his way to the white house to leave his mark, lighting up a blunt as he observed the secret service from afar.
-
the rapper can be seen saying in one clip posted on instagram that while other americans were "doing all this other bullshit" amid the midterm elections, he decided to temporarily camp out nearby the white house to smoke, saying: "f--- the president."
-
#snoop dogg could be seen in other clips walking throughout what appears to be lafayette park while talking to fans with his blunt in hand, making his way over to a few benches.
-
of course, he documented the entire process as his instagram is filled with videos of him doing his thing. along the way, he took some photos with fans and even complimented an elderly man on his hair.
-
the west coast legend was excited about his visit, going a little overboard with posts from the president's home.
-
he has been critical of trump in the past. now, he's fine sparking up in front of his house to send a message. in his words, he just "had 2 do it."

-
at the time, snoop dogg also said that he feels trump supporters are condoning racism.
-
snoop dogg also drew criticism from trump supporters last year after he shot a clown dressed as trump with a toy gun in one of his music video.

text:
have i told you how much i absolutely adore my job? not just for the #travel perks or the fact that i get to work with some of the most interesting people on the planet, but because every single day feels new and bâ€™c i realize how incredibly #lucky i am to have found precisely what i was intended for. as an #advertising creative director, my job title doesnâ€™t sound as #honorable as some others, but over my career, iâ€™m #proud to say iâ€™ve created work to help return abducted children to their homes, bring farmers in the heartland the sort of choices that wonâ€™t cost them their farms and save the lives of over 160k shelter pets... and counting. iâ€™ve had a hand in growing businesses that peopleâ€”from baristas to indie bike dealers to immigrant ceoâ€™sâ€”count on. and thatâ€™s not nothing.

i *absolutely* adore this job and recognize how lucky iâ€™ve been, especially in this last year, when i was having to pull myself through the death-throes of a physically-abusive relationship. not everyone gets this kind of blessing. in fact, according to a 2004 report from the world health organization, up to 60% of victims of intimate partner violence lose their jobs as a result of the abuse.

i can only imagine how low iâ€™d feel if, in addition to my safety and peace and self-esteem, my ex had cost me my career. but the awareness of thisâ€”knowing it happens, seeing it happen to other women in my peripheryâ€”gives me #perspective and fire, both for the workplace i drive up to each day and for the work that needs to be done for #abusevictims. as soon as iâ€™m back from this #businesstrip, imma figure out how to chip away at that terrible stat. please let me know if you want to join me; i hope a few of you will, bâ€™c, as with everything else, together, #wegotthis.
.
.
.

jupiter in scorpio

in 1994 at the us figuring skating championships...1 month before the winter olympics, nancy kerrigan was brutally clubbed leaving her unable to compete.  her rival, tonya harding, swore up and down she had nothing to do with it, but the truth was revealed.  it was discovered that her ex husband and bodyguard conspired to attack kerrigan.  harding was later convicted and given 3 years probation, 500 hours of community service,  160,000 dollar fine...and banned from the us figuring skating association for life.  this was big headlines that year, and yes jupiter was transiting scorpioâ™. it will be interesting to see what's uncovered this time.  #realastrologywayne #astrology #nancykerrigan #tonyaharding #jupiterinscorpio

i call those affected by sexual violence "survivors." i have spent the better part of a year waiting to feel some magical transition from "victim" to "survivor," as if one day i would conquer the key to stopping all of the immeasureable pain havoc wreaked on my life. truthfully, i have yet to feel like a survivor. on most days, i feel robbed and like i am grieving for a version of myself that i am not sure exists anymore. but more importantly, every victim/survivor deserved the right to claim whatever term makes then feel the most comfortable or more accurately represents their feelings.

secondly, we must use our language intentionally. something bad did not happen to me. someone did something bad to me. that someone raped me. it was not an accident, it was not "something bad, it was rape.
it is up to us to frame our trauma because unfortunately the rest of the world will not do it for us, or will do so with victim blaming and stigma. 
#ibelievethem .
.

text:

so, yesterday when my girlfriend text me for a spontaneous road trip- i didnâ€™t even hesitate to say yes- cause my office is mobile if i need it to be! today, as i spoke my truth with the intention to inspire- my baby girl sat in the back seat- she will grow up knowing how iâ€™ve been able to be with her every day since i walked away from my full time job when she was 7 months old.

this is the type of freedom i craved- and work so dang hard for.... better to die fighting for freedom then be a prisoner all the days of your life!

after feeling outraged about @cerclecheungâ€™s post on how she was sexually assaulted by a local photographer she hired during a photoshoot here in nyc. i've decided to write a little guide to women who are about to partake & meet a photographer for the first time.
-
1. check references, ask his past clients what their experience was.
2. meet in a safe location, do not go to his house or to a secluded area
3. if you agree on a nude or sexy shoot, you have the right to bring an escort, (boyfriend, sister friend etc) i always encourage people to bring someone if my wife isn't able to come along and help. if he insists on you coming alone that's a sign that you shouldnâ€™t go alone.
4. if he persists on nudes; don't do it!
5. go with your gut feeling! your gut never lies!
6. if you are sexually assaulted report it to authorities asap. it is not your fault!
-
guys like this, make professionals like me look bad and on behalf of all professional photographers out there, i'd like to apologize to everyone who has been sexually assaulted by their photographer. safety has always been the utmost importance to me, both for me and the models i work with, and if i ever made anyone feel uncomfortable, unsafe or have said anything inappropriate; i'm sorry!!

text_retweet:
repost @laviaminora 
dear agni,
.
kamu tidak sendiri. saya juga penyintas.
di usia 4 tahun, saya dicabuli oleh sepupu sendiri.
tapi saya diam, sebab saya tidak tahu apa yang dia lakukan.
.
kamu tidak sendiri. saya juga korban.
di usia 10 tahun, seorang tukang becak menyekap saya di lorong sekolah, dan menjamah liang senggama saya.
saya cuma mingkem, sebab saya takut dianggap tidak bisa jaga diri.
.
kamu tidak sendiri. saya pernah dilecehkan.
di usia 17 tahun, saya bersepeda di jalanan sepi sambil memakai celana training dan hoodie. tiba-tiba seorang bapak menepuk pantat saya.
saya terdiam, karena ketakutan dan tidak bisa bereaksi apa-apa.
.
dear agni,
.
saya tahu rasanya, karena #sayajuga mengalaminya. mau melawan, tapi merasa tidak berdaya. mau mengadu, tapi takut dibikin malu. mau marah-marah sambil membanting, tapi orang tidak pernah menganggap ini penting.
.
sekarang karenamu, keberanian ini bertunas, agni!
suaramu melengking, memekakkan telinga, menerobos batas-batas timpangnya keadilan. sumbu telah ditarik, dan terimakasih atas api yang kau pantik.
.
mulai hari ini dan seterusnya, kita kawal bersama rasa amanmu, rasa aman para wanita yang masih bersembunyi di balik besar dan kuatnya rasa takut. bukan saatnya untuk kita merasa lemah.
.
dan terima kasih paling besar buatmu karena telah menyadarkan bahwa kita bukan barang yang bisa disejajarkan dengan jamahan!
.
untuk semua wanita yang mengalami hal yang sama, kita adalah agni, dan kita adalah api!

#kitaagni
#metoo 
#sayajuga 
#kamibersamaagni ---

text:
#feminism #taranaburke and #metoo.
tarana burke (born september 12, 1973) is an african-american civil rights activist from the bronx, new york who founded the me too movement. in 2006, burke began using the phrase "me too" to raise awareness of the pervasiveness of sexual abuse and assault in society, and the phrase developed into a broader movement, following the 2017 use of #metoo as a hashtag following the harvey weinstein sexual abuse allegations. time named burke, among a group of other prominent activists dubbed "the silence breakers", as the time person of the year for 2017. burke attends public speaking events across the country and is currently senior director at girls for gender equity.
source: @wikipedia

text: my experience as a new mom shook my world. it broke me and made the new me all at once. i am a planner and a control freak so i thought i had everything under control. little did i know i had to leave that control up to my family because i could do nothing but rest. i meal prepped and i thought this was enough. after a weeks rest i did some laundry and got out of my sweat pants.  this made my usually low blood pressure rocket sky high and my midwife warned me medication was a last resort. relaxation and recuperation was my priority.  i have learned so much going through this experience and i am going to help revolutionize the postpartum care period because moms deserve better. i went into this pregnancy the healthiest i've ever been! so i feel for the ladies who have body issues going into pregnancy. its hard enough as it is! my goal is to inspire you to plan your postpartum recovery and have all the support in the right places for you! not just for your baby. dm me for more on this topic or tune into my podcast coming soon. #postpartum #postpartumrevolution #holisticmamma #momsdeservebetter #birth #bethebestmomyoucanbe #momsfirst

text:
when we educate about sexual health and sexual violence, it can bring up "stuff" for a lot of folks, which can lead to discomfort (we don't mean trauma, just to be clear). sometimes, the discomfort is thrown back onto the messenger for delivering the message that the recipient finds uncomfortable. other times, the recipient tries to shut down the messenger, believing that everyone around them is also feeling uncomfortable. and on some occasions, the messenger is told that these conversations are wrong to have. we acknowledge that talking about sexual health and violence isn't easy because it requires us to do our own work. however, we cannot change what's happening around us without first addressing what's happening within. [image description: black text on a white background with the words "never have i dealt with anything more difficult than my own soul" by imam al-ghazali]

#sexeducation #metoo #metoomovement #justice #healing

text:
today, i gave a presentation on the importance of designing technical and organizational systems to fit our human capabilities and limitations. 
the audience consisted of about 70 people working in tank shipping. 
i concluded my talk by taking the opportunity to talk about #metoo and the narratives shared by 1100 swedish women seafarers. 
not everybody are comfortable listening to these stories. but they need to be told.

one year after, i had hoped that we would see more progress. but it is evident that we need to continue talking about our social work environment and remind ourselves and all decision makers out there of a part of reality as ugly as dickpics.

has this never happened to you?
are you not affected, personally?
great!! then you can still make a change by not being a passive bystander. 
use the powerful voice you have for those without a platform. 
rock the boat.

#womeninshipping 
#womenwhomovestheworld 
#metoo 
#lÃ¤ttaankar #anchorsaweigh 
#maritimesafety

text:
today jupiter moves out of deep, dark, transformative scorpio and into curious, adventurous, thought-provoking, and expansive sagittarius until december 2, 2019. this is a big shift that is going to bring about some big changes. â €
â €
jupiter is the ruler of sagittarius so this move is like coming home. jupiter feels most like itself now and can express its energy in the purest and most natural way. sagittarius immediately follows scorpio, the sign of death, transformation, and shadow. scorpio clears out the baggage that weighs us down and holds us back. this gives sagittarius the freedom it needs to fly off to new lands and explore new ideas. â €
â €
with jupiter in sagittarius, you will be introduced to infinite possibilities and opportunities. jupiter is considered the lucky planet so don't be surprised if you just so happen to stumble into your life purpose over the next 12 months or get a once in a lifetime opportunity. overall, the energy of the world will be much lighter and optimistic. new conversations will be had and a desire to understand other ways of life will begin to develop. the next 12 months is all about exploration. how can i see things with fresh, new eyes?â €
â €
sagittarius is the sign of philosophy so take advantage of anything that allows you to learn something new or better yet, to create your own methods of teaching and sharing information. now is an excellent time to introduce your views to the world. jupiter and sagittarius rule publishing, higher education, broadcasting, and enterprising so finding a platform to voice your opinion will be easier than ever. now is an excellent time to write a book or program, start a business (especially in communication and travel), to go back to school, or to take a siesta and travel for a bit. â €
â €
finally, jupiter always brings some issue to light. jupiter in scorpio brought us the #metoo movement which started within days of this transit. immigration has been a hot topic over recent months and is likely to become an even bigger issue now. don't be surprised if we see some major immigration overhauls. â €
â €
enjoying these astrology posts? be sure to let me know by commenting below. #astrology #spiritelement â €

text:
yesterday i had the opportunity to talk about parker handbags from the perspective of wellness and selfcare and in light of amazing new things coming, i want to say thank you to every one out there doing big things for women and so many thank yous to everyone who has supported parker handbags. 
my journey started with developing a handbag for off body carry that made me feel confident to walk to my car alone, in the dark, after work. 
after realizing that my concern is shared by women everywhere, i have shifted the focus of parker handbags to work toward creating a system that empowers women to actively rewrite the script around sexual harassment and assault, regardless of what they choose to carry. 
all in all, i want to provide woman a way to care for their safety and wellbeing in every situation, in a way that makes them feel beautiful, confident and safe.

the big dream. a hard end to gender based violence because enough is enough. 
#parkerhandbags #stopsexualassault #staysafebeauty #metoo #timesup #functionalfashion #enoughisenough #theperfecthandbag #thefutureisfemale #womanboss #loveyourselfenoughtoprotectyourself

text:
the contender _ senator laine billings hanson (2/2) happy #monologuethursday folks! needless to say, the inspiration for this piece didn't come by chance. these past days have been full of expectations and mixed feelings of hope and fear,Â  and i am so full of joy for how voters decided to show that inclusiveness, love and human rights matter. that we want to change the world for good. that that glass ceiling may not be unbearable, as long as we prove ourselves to be unbreakable.
that a world that protects democracy through strenght and love may be possible, if we have the strenght to stand for it.
together.
love,

text:
as a therapist, i have to work hard to keep my heart open and not bring my work home with me. i work primarily with women and as the #metoo movement continues to grow, i have been holding space for a lot more stories of sexual abuse, assault, harassment, etc. â€¢
i try to remember the amazing men in my life (including my incredible partner and loving father) to help remind myself that there are good guys out there and there is still so much education to be done in our culture. â€¢
may we continue to let our stories be told and may we especially share our stories with the men in our lives that we trust. i believe this will help to raise the awareness of what life is really like for women in our world and will help men become more aware of how their actions impact us and our culture. â€¢
i hope this movement continues to help us heal and prevents our daughters from experiencing the traumas that so many of us have endured during our lives. â€¢
may we all love the life we live...

text:
iâ€™m late to write this, but i voted on monday. despite having been able to vote for the past seven years, this was my first time voting in a non-presidential election. jeez louise thatâ€™s embarrassing to admit. nevertheless, i did it! here are some of the things i voted for: 
_
i voted for the environment
because future generations deserve access to the same outdoor experiences that have so greatly enriched my life.
because not all resources are infinite, and we only get one shot at taking care of a planet.
because climate change disproportionally affects those in need.
and because the outdoor recreation economy comprises $887 billion in consumer spending annually, sustains 7.6 million american jobs, and generates $124.5 billion in federal, state, and local tax revenue. so investing in the outdoors is not only socially responsible, itâ€™s financially necessary. 
_
i voted for women 
because american women in 2018 earn 80.5 cents to every manâ€™s dollar, and itâ€™s estimated that pay parity will not be reached until 2059.
because paid family leave (for both men and women) is still not always guaranteed in the us.
and because one in three american women still experience some form of sexual violence in their lifetime, and thatâ€™s just unacceptable. 
_
i voted for education 
because i was blessed to have primary school teachers who werenâ€™t stressed about being underpaid and undersupplied, and were able to prepare me for a lifetime of intellectual inquiry. 
because a bachelorâ€™s degree is a minimum requirement these days, and students shouldnâ€™t have to be in debt for decades just to acquire one. 
and because the global average rate of return on education per capita is 9% for each additional year of school completed, so we know that investing in students works. 
_
i voted for health
because without adequate public health care, i wouldnâ€™t be alive today. 
because without adequate public health care, my mother wouldnâ€™t have watched me graduate college. 
and because if we had all-around better access to preventative health care, maybe she, and millions of others, would still be here.
_

text:
â€œthe women in my paintings are not based on any one specific female or feminine figure in my life but a plethora of many women. women have been a direct influence to a multitude of positive and significant transitions throughout my life experiences. especially in the direction towards an art career. in this present state i live in a world of massive gender inequality and iâ€™m making it my personal responsibility as a man to use my voice creatively to bring attention and awareness to the strength, passion, resilience, innovation and beauty that women can offer to the world. if we allow women to receive equal opportunities and treatment there can only be amazing positivity and growth for us as human beings. the power of creation and the universe itself exists within the woman and without her we as humans could never be.

my voice stands with her voice, and each line i create builds a step towards equality for her.

(and i promise, now weâ€™re done talking about kanye! iâ€™d rather be taylor swift, anyway.)
.

.

.

text:
meet our team! 
sophie is the projectâ€™s developer and director. sheâ€™s a belgian-american who earned a film, international development, and womenâ€™s studies degree from @mcgillu before moving to toronto in 2016. sheâ€™s worked as a journalist for the @thetorontostar, a producer for @sidlee_official, a publicity coordinator for @wearealphapr, & is currently casting ads and short films with @jigsawcasting. 
after being assaulted and beaten in toronto just weeks after she moved here, she has done what she can to change the dialogue around assault. 
she promoted documentary about mandi grayâ€™s legal struggle against her rapist, @slutornutthemovie, ahead of its ultimately-soldout hot docs premiere, was asked to speak on a podcast about the kavanaugh confirmation, and is a writer for @ramonaforgirls, publishing pieces several times a year - under pseudonym sophie rose - about life after trauma.

she started the survivor project because she wanted to keep facilitating change around how people talk, conceive of, manage, and contextualize assault. she has a dedication to finding ways for assault survivors of all backgrounds and creeds to heal, grow, and feel less alone. the project aims to give toronto survivors a space, a community, and a voice. 
#thesurvivorproject #women #inspirational #strong #blackandwhite #film #toronto #metoo #meet #meetandgreet #woman

text:
how will you best describe your childhood experience?

was it good, exciting, full of adventures or is a time you don't want to remember?

think!

how then do you want your children to remember theirs?

let's raise children who will not have to recover from their childhood.

text:
tanzania has one of the highest rates of child marriages in the entire world. today, 37% of girls are forced into marriage before they have reached their 18th birthday. in fact, 2 out of 5 girls are married before they are 18 years old. traditional customs condone harassment and violence towards women. cases of violence usually go unreported. the cases that are reported are usually settled outside of court. discrimination also happens inside the classroom. the girls who actually get the chance to go to school can be automatically expelled if they are married or pregnant. in rural villages women who are older in years get accused of being witches and then are violently attacked. studies have shown that in 2013, 505 women in tanzania had witchcraft-related murders.

this is why the rafiki exchange strives to help widows in africa, including tanzania. we teach these women the bible. they now have an opportunity to learn about a loving god who sent his son to die for sinners, the one who created the world, a god who knows their every need. the rafiki exchange gives an opportunity for women to work and support themselves and their children. giving them an option which was nearly impossible before. we believe in helping women in need across africa. women who often times have no voice, women who are forgotten. we are passionate about this important work.
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text:
forced marriages, sexual abuse, and wife inheritance is all prevalent in the 8 million widows living in kenya. when you consider that kenya has some of the most oppressed widows in the world living in it, those 8 million lives suddenly seem to be more important. in a study done in 2016 the widows in kenya were ranked 33rd in the world for most devastated lifestyle. 
when her husband dies, the in-laws usually try and take the land from the widow he leaves behind. if the widow's land is taken from her by the in-laws, what choice does she have but to comply? if she protests them taking the land and takes the matter to court, what will happen if she wins? she will have a home but will then be completely ostracized by her clan. she may have four walls and a roof over her head, but living in a village where no one will speak to you would be a tragic life. it seems far safer to let them take the home and property. 
in most cases, widows end up blamed for their husband's death and cast out of society with no belongings. with no property, no home, and no one to turn to for help, the widow is left alone. 
this is why rafiki's work with widows is so important. we come along side these women and help them support themselves in a way that was not possible before. it is our hope that you will come along side of us and help give lasting hope to future generations of widows in kenya. â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text:
in 1994 the finish of the rwandan genocide, which came from a 100 day mass murder from the hutu and tutsi tribes, left over 800,000 people dead. studies show that 1 in 10 rwandans died during these 100 days. the effects of having almost 1 million people die in less than four months is staggering. rwanda quickly became a country with more women than men. the scars and trauma these women carry with them is both tragic and inspiring. they survived things most of us couldnâ€™t even dream of. they watched their children and husbands get hacked into bits by men with machetes, or were trapped while their neighbors were violently clubbed to death. their homes were destroyed and burned to the ground while they were forced to watch. for a lot of these women, what they went through after watching this unfold, would be what some would call a fate worse than death. violent rapings were condoned and these women suffered in the most extreme ways because of it. some were left after all this took place to, â€œdie of sadness.â€ after the genocide finished, these widows were left to pick up the pieces, and somehow make a new life. with their husbands dead, the widows from the hutu and tutsi tribes came together and made peace. by weaving baskets together these women found a way of healing in something that has been a part of rwandan culture for centuries. the weaving and selling of these baskets to western markets has gained the rwandan widows economic independence and improved their local communities. 
now, 24 years later, 50% of homes in rwanda are run by women. the women in this country still live in extreme poverty. often $1.25 a day or less is what they have to feed and shelter themselves and their children. they are slowly rebuilding. the rafiki exchange has partnered with these very women, and are selling their baskets in our local exchanges, on our online exchange, and our new etsy shop. we are passionate about helping these widows support themselves and their children. this is work that you can be apart of. click the link in our bio to shop the rafiki exchange and support these widows in rwanda. â€¢

in 1994 the finish of the rwandan genocide, which came from a 100 day mass murder from the hutu and tutsi tribes, left over 800,000 people dead. studies show that 1 in 10 rwandans died during these 100 days. the effects of having almost 1 million people die in less than four months is staggering. rwanda quickly became a country with more women than men. the scars and trauma these women carry with them is both tragic and inspiring. they survived things most of us couldnâ€™t even dream of. they watched their children and husbands get hacked into bits by men with machetes, or were trapped while their neighbors were violently clubbed to death. their homes were destroyed and burned to the ground while they were forced to watch. for a lot of these women, what they went through after watching this unfold, would be what some would call a fate worse than death. violent rapings were condoned and these women suffered in the most extreme ways because of it. some were left after all this took place to, â€œdie of sadness.â€ after the genocide finished, these widows were left to pick up the pieces, and somehow make a new life. with their husbands dead, the widows from the hutu and tutsi tribes came together and made peace. by weaving baskets together these women found a way of healing in something that has been a part of rwandan culture for centuries. the weaving and selling of these baskets to western markets has gained the rwandan widows economic independence and improved their local communities. 
now, 24 years later, 50% of homes in rwanda are run by women. the women in this country still live in extreme poverty. often $1.25 a day or less is what they have to feed and shelter themselves and their children. they are slowly rebuilding. the rafiki exchange has partnered with these very women, and are selling their baskets in our local exchanges, on our online exchange, and our new etsy shop. we are passionate about helping these widows support themselves and their children. this is work that you can be apart of. click the link in our bio to shop the rafiki exchange and support these widows in rwanda. â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢

text:
widowhood in uganda is a hardship that most of us cannot possibly fathomâ€”11% of women over 15 years old are widows. studies show that 50% of these widows are illiterate, 67% work in other peopleâ€™s gardens for survival, and 61% survive on less than 5,000 ugandan shillings a weekâ€“less than two american dollars. shortly after her husband dies, the widow is subjected to the common ugandan practice of â€œproperty grabbing.â€ this is the intentional driving out of the vulnerable woman and her dependents from their homes and land by physical force, threats, intimidation, and property destruction. studies have shown that over 18% of widows that go through property grabbing have also experienced attempts on their lives. even so, the women cling tenaciously to their homes and property. why wouldnâ€™t they? their children need shelterâ€”a place to lay their heads at night and carry on in life. in spite of their resistance to the property grabbing, 17% still see their homes and property viciously destroyed in the process. the plight of the ugandan widows is unconscionable.
â€¢
â€¢
â€¢
#africa #uganda #ugandan #african #widows #widowsandorphans #helingothers #nonprofit #africanweavers #handwoven #rafiki #rafikifoundation #rafikiexchange #metoo

text:
my sister @stealthlikemi and huzzband @unityofnoise have a new heart wrenching song being released tomorrow. my sister has been struggling with multiple hardships emotionally, down to the cellular level. trying to still function in a world that doesnâ€™t stop spinning to allow her the time to grab a hold of her health. when things are looking up they take another left turn. we as a family support her and help as much as we can from a distance. 
tomorrow when the song gets released my family is getting the semi-colon tattooed on ourselves... as we all can relate to itâ€™s new meaning and also in support of my sisters struggles. we have all been there at some point in our lives. just thankful at different times so we can be a rock for others when needed. 
project semicolon, which offers hope to those struggling with depression, suicide, addiction and self-injury, borrows its philosophy from the punctuation mark in its name. â€œa semicolon is used when an author could've chosen to end their sentence, but chose not to,â€ the project's website reads. â€œthe author is you and the sentence is your life.â€ i have lost friends to suicide and addiction. i have personally struggled with anxiety and depression. my sisters song and jimâ€™s minimal production really hits me deep in my soul. 
i hope you all connect and have a listen, and support not only music, but my sisters form of art work. $1 for a song, to own a piece of artwork seems crazy right?
music is taken for granted more then ever, and people expect it for free when it takes years of time, energy and emotional release to finish a piece of music. not only that, but it is like winning the lottery to make a living off of music these days, so while my sister is a true artist, she losses herself when she goes to her corporate job that can support her family and retain benefits. 
the struggle is real. what would the world be without artists? #newmusic #amazonmusic #itunesmusic #spotify #alternative #singer  #songwriter #femalesongwriter #producer #unityofnoise #harp #strings #piano  #mentalhealthawareness #mentalhealth #semicolon #semicolonart #semicolontattoo #semicolonproject @sufferingthesilence #afsp #metoo @reborn.social @
name: Melis Fusco

text:
we are a collective of survivors and allies in toronto working to help heal those affected by sexual assault. 
december 2018 - a safe space for toronto survivors to gather in small numbers and partake in food, art, company, and affirmation. those who wish to tell their stories, speak their truths, read letters, vent, & more are encouraged to spend time in our recording booth, where they are given a platform and a voice they may have felt they were lacking. 
2019 - a short film, based on and around the anonymous testimony given by survivors during the event. 
this is to help the survivors of every age, race, creed, sexuality, status whoâ€™ve felt helpless, voiceless, angry, upset, triggered during this period in which #metoo and rape culture has been so prevalently public. this is to help disseminate information and affect about the range and reality of assault in our city. this is to help us understand where our cultureâ€™s going wrong. this is to help however we can. 
if you have questions, or if youâ€™d like to be involved, please be in touch. 
information on the event coming very soon ğŸ–¤

text:
ğŸ¤­ okay so the immature side or the prudish side, not sure which, may squirm uneasily in my seat. but i ask myself why is thatâ“ â—the people pleaser in me, says don't post it, you'll offend someone. â—the 'need to justify' in me, says don't post it, people will think you hate men. i don't. â—the 'girl' in me says don't post it, you'll be called a slag. âœŠğŸ½the women in me posted it. 
why? no it's not because i love talking about sex. in fact, i'm quite private when it comes to affairs of the bedroom. (just the fact i referred to it as affairs of the bedroom is evidence alone!)
i'm private because i choose to be not because i'm ashamed. as always, each to their own, no judgement here.

i posted it because it is a fair point to be made. women can't casually refer to their sexual pleasure as men do, as their simply isn't the language to do so. it's not that i'm saying i think we should all shout about 'getting off', like i said, i'm private... i suppose i'm using it as a vehicle to highlight how, if the choice of  vocabulary is there, it can have a significant impact on the way we perceive, think and accept situations/ideas. without the vocab we cannot express=only one angle exposed. what choice does that leave? "the way we think is so related to language" so if their isn't the language how do we learn to expand our thinking?

thank you to @theonly_louaimeshill
for sharing this! ğŸ¤” and @holliepoetry
for giving me the words.

text:
we're joining in with #museum30 this month and today is â€˜controversial'. for today's museum30 weâ€™re sharing a post from our girl reviews series, in which contributing writer michelle oâ€™brien writes: "this plot point is troublesome for a number of reasons. the first is that jake views caroline is his property and he can trade her for something that he wants. if he cared at all about his girlfriend he would have made sure she got home safely. the second issue is that the geek gives her still more alcohol and takes pictures with her so he has proof of his â€œconquestâ€. caroline was already drunk and did not want or need any more alcohol; additionally, taking photos without her consent is unacceptable. the third problem stems from caroline waking up without any memory of what happened, and yet she says that she feels likes she enjoyed herself. we donâ€™t see what happened between caroline and the geek, but it is implied they had sex. even though she doesnâ€™t remember it and she was too drunk to consent, this is never addressed by her or ted. it implies that this sort of behaviour is acceptable and it simply is not.
i was in college the first time i watched this movie and i found the entire movie problematic (honestly i disliked every character). if i had watched this when i was younger and more impressionable it could have had a much bigger impact on me. with the #metoo and #timesup movements reviewing problematic portrayals of women on tv and in movies has become a popular topic. if you are interested in reading more about this i strongly recommend reading molly ringwaldâ€™s article where she goes into far more detail on this topic." read the fill blog at http://girlmuseum.org

i believe that the heart can re-grow, expand, into a stronger state than she's ever been. i need to constantly feed her a lot of love, and a lot of love she deserves and needs.

text:
our soars 20th anniversary tour continues..next stop, atlanta georgia! we are headed to atlanta for the national womenâ€™s association conference @nwsa_ig !! the spoken-word poet you see on stage, anaya patrice frazier, girl/friend youth leader, who performed a poem this summer about the missing & murdered black girls on the south & west side of chicago will be taking the stage with legendary reproductive justice organizer loretta ross,  national campus activist wagatwe wanjuki @wagatwe, revolutionary filmmaker @afrolez aisha simmons, radical black feminist photographer & youth community organizer @sherphotographs scheherazade tillet, writer, educator, and organizer @salamishah and girl/friends youth leader danielle nolen to yâ€™all about â€œgive my consent never: black women and girls revolutionizing the anti-rape movement.â€
*
*
this panel will build off the concept from the combahee river collective statement, â€œif black women were free, it would mean that everyone else would have to be free,â€ & engages four generations of black women artists and activists to historicize and to reflect on the vanguard roles that they and others have played in the movement to end sexual violence before and beyond #metoo

#soars20 #gotconsent #nwsa

text:
in may 2018 we officially launched she matters tribe in nairobi, kenya. we have seen our community grow to thousands of women from around the world. weâ€™ve shared our stories, weâ€™ve shared our struggles, and now weâ€™re taking action. 
___
today we launch the she matters reporting platform. by survivors, for survivors. 
while we encourage all survivors to report sexual assault cases to police and seek medical treatment in hospital, we too understand that thousands of survivors worldwide face intolerance, disbelief, and insensitivity when reporting. 
far too many of us have been told we are not believed. 
far too many of us have been told â€œwe looked like we enjoyed itâ€. far too many of us have been questioned about our level of alcohol consumption, or what we wore - as if that were justification for rape. 
we are here for you. 
the she matters reporting platform will allow you to report anonymously, or with your identity, malpractice or insensitivity from law enforcement or medical professionals when reporting sexual assault. 
we are holding our community stakeholders accountable, and working towards a strengthened system where we are believed and supported. 
___
your voice matters. 
you are not alone. 
weâ€™re stronger together! [link in bio]

text:
jupiter moves into sagittarius today.
.
.
.
heâ€™s been settled in scorpio for the past 13 months, forcing us to uncover uncomfortable truths about death, sexuality, our darkness and shadows... itâ€™s actually quite obvious when you look at it on the collective levelâ€”the advent of the #metoo movement, gender equality issues, etc.
.
jupiter in scorpio has been a lot. itâ€™s been an exhausting adventure. so much darkness has been exposed to the light. you know when your eyes have adjusted to the darkness and you suddenly flip on the light and youâ€™re like â€œoh god my eyes!â€ because itâ€™s so bright and blinding? but then eventually your eyes readjust to the light and you start to see things for what they are? thatâ€™s kind of like this transition from jupiter in scorpio into jupiter in sag. the lights are on. sagittarius is the archer, aiming to open the mind and open the heart. sagittarius is expansive and good natured energy.
.
a caveat: thereâ€™s a challenging cosmic friction point coming up where mars will square jupiter in the middle of the month through the end of the year, so remain steadfast in your commitment to move forward into the light with as much positivity as you can possibly muster. find your strength and allow your new understanding of your shadows to propel you forth. as we make this transition out of the shadows and into the light, keep coming back to the lessons learned from the darkness.
.

in a nutshell: boldly ask the universe for what you want, and be open to all the ways in which it will provide. remember, an archer must draw his bow backward before it can fly forward. keep aiming. ğŸ¹

text:
how easy is it to bring gratitudes to your life?

a lot of people say they don't have time to do daily gratitudes.. - 
so i wanted to make a video to show everyone just how quick it is to bring gratitudes to your daily life.. - 
they are so powerful and they take less than 90 seconds... - 
less than 90 seconds and they are just as powerful as some depression medication?! - 
yep. - 
make time for these, i promise you won't regret it :) - 
watch the full video on youtube: overcoming ptsd

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

text:

if you donate even just $1, leave a comment or dm me and i'll send you a bff, beer food fun sticker to show my appreciation! thank you.

text:
wylie said that bannon's plans began to solidify in 2014, when cambridge analytica consulted various republican campaigns and pacs ahead of the midterm elections. the company began to test and apply its psychographics by using facebook data to model individuals' personality types in order to understand how to influence them.

documents show the john bolton super pac, which promoted candidates supported by recently appointed white house national security adviser john bolton, paid cambridge analytical $454,700 in 2014 for "behavioral microtargeting with psychographic messaging." those services included strategies that broke individual voters into "clusters" based on what messages would resonate with them.

wylie also said the company used focus groups and messaging trials in 2014 to test some of the concepts that became core themes of the trump campaign, such as "drain the swamp" and imagery of walls. "a lot of the narratives of the trump campaign were what we were testing in 2014," wylie said.

he added that bannon directly presided over much of the company's initial research. "everything that we were doing ultimately had to be passed up to bannon for approval," said wylie, who left the company in late 2014.

wylie said bannon would fly to london about once a month for company meetings, and during that time he came to understand bannon's ideology. "he really liked the idea of using a military-style approach to changing people's perceptions," wylie said.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan & drew griffin
cnn

text:
bannon wanted to use the sorts of aggressive messaging tactics usually reserved for geopolitical conflicts to move the us electorate further to the right, wylie said. he had already directed a series of anti-establishment, conservative documentary films and presided over the far-right website breitbart news, but cambridge analytica would mark another step in his overall ambitions to transform the nation.

with financial backing from hedge-fund billionaire robert mercer, bannon co-founded cambridge analytica in 2013 as the us-branch of strategic communication laboratories (scl) group, a british company that advertises how it has conducted "behavioral change" programs in more than 60 countries.

wylie described cambridge analytica as - steve bannon and robert mercer using a foreign, military contractor ... to use some of the same techniques that the military uses ... on the american electorate.

curt devine, donie o'sullivan and drew griffin
cnn

abusing and leaking presidential information to mislead the people and benefit the hijacked party of puppets is obviously just business as usual.

and here comes the best part. trumq is truly playing along with his tweets, gestures and words.

the bigger issue still is that requqlicans are willingly piggybacking this lunacy and abusing the faith of their fellow men while campaigning for the midterms. this is not just an insane national security risk - it's a leaking conspiracy and treason in plain sight.
